sentences: Patterson was born on June 17, 1931 in New Haven, Connecticut.
He attended Greenwich High School from 1946 to 1950 and then spent one year at The Tilton School, where he played for Coach Weldon Haire.
Patterson played guard for the UConn Huskies from 1951 to 1954.

During that time he was named  first team All-Yankee Conference twice (1952–53 and 1953–54) and helped lead the team to three consecutive Yankee Conference Championships and an appearance in the 1954 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament.
Patterson signed with the Celtics shortly before the start of training camp in 1954.
In 1957, Patterson returned to professional basketball as a member of the St. Louis Hawks.
After his release, Patterson worked in the Hawks' front office for 4–6 weeks as part of the team's effort to integrate.
In 1969, he was appointed manager of artist relations east at Dot Records.
In 1970, he returned to RCA as head of promotions.
In 1971, Patterson was promoted to Sales Director.
In 1972, Patterson became Eastern district sales manager for Warner/Reprise Records.
In 1973, he joined Warner Brothers’ subsidiary Casablanca Records, where he was charge of promotions for the new label.
He worked at Bertelsmann Music Group for eight months in 1991 before retiring.
